observations.recommendation:
Prepare and maintain subsidiary ledgers for Cash in Bank-Local Currency Current Account;


Prepare appropriate BRS for all bank accounts of the Municipality by reconciling the bank statements with the subsidiary ledgers for Cash in Bank-Local Currency Current Account; and

If necessary, augment personnel in the Accounting Department to prioritize the preparation and submission of the required BRS.

Create an inventory committee composed of adequate number of members with members from the Accounting Unit and GSO and enjoin them to conduct the one-time cleansing of PPE accounts of the Municipality in accordance with the prescribed procedures embodied in COA Circular 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020;

Require the GSO and Municipal Accountant to prepare and maintain the Property Cards and PPE Ledger Cards and reconcile both records regularly;

If necessary, provide additional manpower at the Accounting Office and GSO to aide in the preparation of records/reports and in the supply and property management of the LGU;

After the conduct of inventory taking, direct the inventory committee to prepare and submit the following to the Audit Team in the prescribed format:

Report on Physical Count of PPE (RPCPPE);
Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP), if there are unserviceable properties found during inventory taking;
Request for Relief from Accountability by Accountable persons for lost PPE items under their accountability, if any;
Journal Entry Vouchers drawn by the Accounting Unit for recognition of loss of PPE from concerned accountable officers/ personnel, if any, and other necessary adjusting entries.

We recommended that management:
Direct the Municipal Accountant to file an application for Land Bank’s weAccess online facility for real-time viewing of account statements and improve lead time in the preparation of BRS;
Make a representation with UCPB Savings Bank to directly send bank statements to the Accounting Unit on a monthly basis otherwise avail of the bank’s online facility for viewing of bank statements, if any;
Prepare and maintain subsidiary ledgers for Cash in Bank-Local Currency Current Account;
Thereafter, prepare appropriate BRS for all bank accounts of the Municipality by reconciling the bank statements and Cashbooks with the subsidiary ledgers for Cash in Bank-Local Currency Current Account; and
If necessary, augment personnel in the Accounting Department to prioritize the preparation and submission of the required BRS.

We recommended that management:
Create an inventory committee composed of adequate number of members with members from the Accounting Unit and GSO;
Consider reconstituting the manpower at the GSO office to avoid holding concurrent positions to fully focus their time and effort in the supply and property management of the LGU;
If necessary, provide additional manpower at the Accounting Office and GSO to aide in the preparation of records/reports and in the supply and property management of the LGU;
Subsequently, require the GSO and Municipal Accountant to: for current purchases onwards - reconcile PPE Ledger Cards and Property Cards regularly and conduct physical count, pending completion of one-time cleansing; and
Given the enormity of workload involving one time-cleansing of PPE, consider implementing the PPE cleansing by phase (i.e. by PPE class). Thereafter, require the Inventory Committee and the Accountant to submit to the audit Team the reports and documents required under COA Circular No. 2020-006 as appropriate, for verification.

We recommended that management:
Require concerned municipal officials or project focal person to furnish a copy of the MOA to the Municipal Accountant.  If no MOA is available, instruct the municipal treasurer and the accountant to communicate to the Source Agencies (SAs) a written request for a copy of the MOA for the subject fund transfers;
Maintain a centralized filing of MOA under the Mayor’s Office for easy retrieval of records;
Direct the implementing department heads or focal persons to determine the project status and submit status reports and other relevant documents to the Municipal Accountant for the liquidation of funds; and
If projects are already completed and no outstanding obligations accrue to the funds, return immediately the unexpended balance to the source agencies.  If the SA cannot be identified, remit the remaining idle funds to the Bureau of Treasury pursuant to DOF, DBM and COA Joint Circular No. 4-2012 dated September 11, 2012 which prescribes the rules and regulations implementing Executive Order (E.O.) No. 431 dated May 20, 2005 directing the reversion of all dormant accounts, unnecessary special and trust funds to the general fund of the national treasury.

Relieve the Municipal Treasurer from her designation as OIC-Municipal Assessor and fill-up the the mandatory position of Municipal Assessor to take charge of the assessor’s office and perform the duties provided under Book II of the Local Government Code;

Thereafter direct the Municipal Assessor to furnish the Assessment Roll to the Municipal Treasurer as basis for the latter’s preparation of a duly certified list of taxpayers with corresponding amount of tax due and collectible for the year which should be the basis of the Municipal Accountant in the set-up of RPT/SET Receivables; 

Require the Municipal Accountant to effect adjusting entries to rectify the noted understatement of the RPT/SET Receivables and Deferred RPT/SET Income; and

Direct the Municipal Collectors to require from the taxpayers the revised Tax Declarations upon payment to ensure that the revised assessed values are used in the computation of taxes due.

Transfer the unexpended balances of QRF and DRRMF-MOOE to the Special Trust Fund under the account “Trust Liability -DRRM” in the Trust Fund books after determining the accurate amount of unspent LDRRMF from CYs 2019 to 2022;

Maintain subsidiary records by year of transfer for the unutilized DRRMF to the special trust fund; 

Reconcile the bank balance of DRRM-TF with the balances per Cash in Bank, LCCA SL, Treasurer’s Cashbook and Trust Liabilities-DRRM account and effect necessary adjusting entries; and

Instruct the LDRRMO to prepare the LDRRMF Investment Plan which shall incorporate the list of projects and activities charged to the unexpended LDRRMF of previous years.

Follow strictly the guidelines as prescribed under COA Circular No. 2013-004 and its applicable annexes and templates in the installation of project signboards; 

Include the cost of signboards in the Approved Budget for the Contract and Program of Works; and

For projects implemented by contract, include the installation of signboards as a checklist item in the supporting documents before obligating payment of the first partial billing to the contractors.

We have recommended that management to:
Require the MAO, MNAO and the LDRRMO to submit to the GSO and the Municipal Accountant the Acknowledgement Receipts of the donations they have received and the list of beneficiaries with whom the donations were distributed, copy furnished the Office of the Auditor;
Streamline and document its donation policy and process thru the issuance of an Executive Order or a Memorandum, which among others, would contain the employees authorized to receive donations and their reportorial responsibilities.

We have recommended the management to:
a. Establish specific guidelines on the grants of AICS and other financial assistance to indigent constituents which shall be in line with DSWD Memorandum Circular No. 11, series of 2019: Revised Guidelines on the Implementation of Assistance to Individuals in Crisis Situation to ensure equitable distribution of financial assistance among the qualified beneficiaries;
b. Ensure that only the MSWDO personnel access and evaluate applicants requesting financial assistance out of the AICS program including the determination of the amount of assistance to be provided;
c. Establish partnerships with stakeholders such as hospitals, drugstores/pharmacies, transport companies/travel agencies, funeral parlors and other service providers to ensure that referred clients are able to receive the needed services immediately. Memorandum of Agreement (MOA) may be entered into by the LGU with qualified service providers in accordance with pertinent regulations.

We have recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
Create an inventory committee composed of adequate number of members with members from the Accounting Unit and Treasury Unit (in the absence of a separate Supply Unit) and enjoin them to conduct the one-time cleansing of PPE accounts of the Municipality in accordance with the prescribed procedures embodied in COA Circular 2020-006 dated January 31, 2020 to establish PPE balances that are verifiable as to existence, condition and accountability;
Provide additional manpower at the Office of the Municipal Treasurer to aide the Municipal Treasurer in the supply and property management of the LGU;
After the conduct of inventory taking, direct the inventory committee to prepare and submit the following to the Audit Team in the prescribed format:
Report on Physical Count of PPE (RPCPPE);
Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP), if there are unserviceable properties found during inventory taking;
Request for Relief from Accountability by Accountable persons for lost PPE items under their accountability, if any;
Journal Entry Vouchers drawn by the Accounting Unit for recognition of loss of PPE from concerned accountable officers/ personnel, if any, and other necessary adjusting entries.

We have recommended the management to require the RHU In-Charge to submit inventory report upon acquisition of donated drugs and medicines to the Accounting Office;

Require the RHU Inventory In-Charge to submit the monthly report of issuances to the Municipal Accountant as basis for the recording of expenses for inventories consumed or distributed; and

Direct the RHU Inventory In-Charge to prepare and update the stock cards regularly and reconcile it with the results of physical inventory count at least on a semestral basis.

We have recommended the management to require the Accounting Office to record first the purchases of drugs and medicines as inventory;

 Require the RHU Inventory In-Charge to submit the monthly report of issuances to the Municipal Accountant as basis for the recording of expenses for inventoried consumed or distributed;

 Direct the RHU Inventory In-Charge to prepare and update the stock cards regularly and reconcile it with the results of physical inventory count at least on a semestral basis; and

Require the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Budget Officer proper charging of accounts and reclass accounts affected;

We reiterated our recommendations to management to prioritize the completion of inventory taking and submit the RPCPPE; 

	To direct the Accounting Office and Municipal Treasurer’s Office to maintain updated Supplies/Property Ledger Cards and Stock/Property and Equipment Cards, respectively, using the prescribed format as provided under the NGAS for LGUs.  The assigned personnel should further be instructed to make a regular reconciliation of records and monitor the utilization of supplies; and

	The physical inventory of supplies and property, plant and equipment shall be reconciled with the Supplies/Property and Equipment Ledger Cards as maintained in the Accounting Office and Stock/Property Cards as maintained in the Municipal Treasurer’s Office, any discrepancies should be immediately verified and adjusted.

We have recommended the management to require the Municipal Accountant to reclassify the completed projects to the appropriate Property, Plant and Equipment account in compliance with COA Circular No. 2015-009 dated December 1, 2015; 

	To recognize appropriate Due to accounts for completed projects to close the CIP accounts; and

Compute the required depreciation on the completed projects and accordingly adjust the balances of the affected accounts.

